      "Expect a small pinch for IV placement, then a period of relaxation while the infusion runs. Possible mild coolness in the arm, metallic taste with some B vitamins, or brief warmth—usually normal. Rarely, bruising or phlebitis can occur; we monitor and respond. Hydrate and eat beforehand unless directed otherwise. Afterward, most clients resume routine activities the same day. Frequency depends on your plan and provider guidance—not daily use for everyone. Oswego, Naperville, Aurora, and Plainfield clients appreciate our calming environment and medical oversight. We answer questions before, during, and after your drip. Bring a light jacket and phone charger; many guests read or answer email during the infusion. If you feel chest tightness, severe shortness of breath, or unusual symptoms, alert staff immediately—we are trained to respond.",
